A pair of stridently coloured slippers, so loud they should have come with earplugs, is proffered by a man in a flapping robe. ‘You want? You buy? Verigood, sir! Very, vairree cheap!’

I didn’t want, I replied, I wouldn’t buy. I shook my head and walked on quickly. However, in this part of the world, refusal to buy is interpreted as a cunning bargaining device.

Obviously I must have wanted a colourful pair of slippers – and my speedy departure simply meant I was hoping to bring down the price.

